  <h4>Decision Time</h4>

  <p>It was time to decide how to handle responsivenes.</p>

  <h4>Framework or no framework?</h4>

  <p>I decided to hand-roll the responsiveness and here's why. The primary function of a CSS framework (Bootstrap / Materialize / Fountation / Semantic UI) would have been to easily implement a responsive layout. These frameworks however come with A TON of additional style rules that often need to be overridden and wrestled with. It can be rather annoying to import hundreds of lines of styles simply to implement a feature (responsiveness) that takes merely a dozen lines of CSS at most.</p>

  <p>For the sake of exploration / experimentation, I decided to investigate <a href="http://semantic-ui.com/">Semantic UI</a>, the least invasive CSS framework in my opinion. I've used it successfully in the past and thought it was worth a try again for this project.</p>

  <p>I installed Semantic and, lo and behold, it stubbornly began to enchroach upon my ability to control the typography. After fiddling with it for a while I decided it would take an equal amount of time to simply learn the principles of <a href="https://css-tricks.com/snippets/css/a-guide-to-flexbox/">CSS flexbox</a>, a process that indeed only took half an hour and undoubtedly saved me time from not having to wrestle with Semantic's framework styles.</p>

  <p>This hand-rolled responsive solution gave me only what I needed and nothing extra. It made the CSS more readable and maintainable, and eliminated the need to load an extra CSS framework library. Now, sitting neatly in my toolbox is a 12-line solution to the problem of responsive web design and, needless to say, I am pleased with this.</p>

